설명: Created by Bertito "Tito" Beveridge, a Texas native, this vodka sold its first bottles in 1997. His distillery located in Austin, Texas, is the first legal distillery in Texas since Prohibition. Millions of bottles have been sold since. Tito's is made from 100% corn and is gluten free.

Absolut is produced in the town of Åhus in Sweden from locally-grown winter wheat. First introduced to the US in 1979, its iconic apothecary bottle is recognizable around the world. Absolut was first introduced in 1879 as Absolut Rent Brännvin (absolutely pure vodka) by Lars Olsson Smith. It is he who adorns the silver medallion on each bottle.

Grey Goose launched in 1997 and is one of the first super premium vodkas to hit the market. It is made from French winter wheat sourced from farms in Picardy in northern France. It is column-distilled and sent to Cognac where demineralized spring water from the region is added to bring the vodka to proof.

First launched in 1983, Ketel One is made from 100% GMO-free European wheat. It is distilled in a combination of column and pot-distillation, including the original 19th century coal-fired pot still named "Distilleerketel #1". The image of this still, or ketel, adorns each bottle. The two distillates are blended together along with water to create this vodka. Bottled at 40% ABV.

Reyka's distillery is located in the town of Bogarnes on the west coast of Iceland. Barley grain spirit (barley and some wheat) is brought to them from Scotland where it is redistilled in a single distillation in a copper-lined Carter-Head still. Each batch produces about 255 cases and takes six hours to complete. The vodka is filtered through lava rock and the water used to bring the vodka to proof is arctic spring water. The distillery is powered by geothermal energy from underground volcanoes and as a result, produces zero emissions.

First introduced to the US in 1996 as a luxury vodka, Belvedere Vodka is distilled from 100% Polish Dankowskie rye. It is distilled using a four-column still process. Belvedere uses water drawn from wells situated in the grounds of the distillery to bring it to proof and then charcoal filters the vodka prior to bottling. The brand's name means "beautiful to see".

Smirnoff No. 21 Vodka, now made in several countries around the world, has origins in Russia. In 1864, Pyotr Smirnov founded his distillery in Moscow. Years later under his heirs' ownership, the distillery was lost during the Russian Revolution in 1917 when the Bolsheviks took control. Vladimir, one of the sons, fled and wound up in France where he established another distillery. He gave that distillery a French version of his last name, Smirnoff. In 1934, Vladimir sold the rights to Rudolph Kunett to sell Smirnoff in the US and Canada where Kunett had established a distillery in Connecticut. The ownership has changed a few times, but is now owned by Diageo. Smirnoff is distilled via continuous distillation and made from grain. It is charcoal filtered and bottled at 40% ABV. Note: As of October 2018, Smirnoff No. 21 is now made with non-GMO grain, specifically non-GMO corn. It is gluten free. Updated packaging as well.
Russian Standard is the entry-level vodka in this portfolio. It is distilled in St. Petersburg from 100% Russian winter wheat and filtered through charcoal and quartz crystal. Bottled at 40% ABV.

Created in California in 1992, SKYY is distilled via four-column distillation from 100% American grains. It uses pure filtered water and is triple-filtered. Made in the USA. Please note: As of May 2021, SKYY Vodka has been reformulated to include water enriched with Pacific minerals. The brand has also updated its packaging for the bottle.

Wheatley Vodka is distilled at the Buffalo Trace Distillery under supervision by master distiller, Harlen Wheatley and his team. Primarily a wheat-based vodka, there are other grains that are used in its production. Distilled in a "micro-still", the vodka is triple-filtered and bottled at 82 proof.

Chopin Potato Vodka was first launched in 1992 and was first introduced to the US in 1997. This family-owned brand produces single ingredient vodkas with no flavored vodkas in their portfolio. Their 100% potato vodka is made mostly from potatoes sourced within 25 miles of the distillery, some of which they grow themselves. They are cooked whole with their skins prior to fermentation. The vodka is distilled in a copper column-still. Bottled at 40% ABV.
Created by Jean-Sébastien Robicquet, CÎROC Vodka is made from 100% French grapes, primarily ugni blanc. It was first launched in the US in 2003.
First launched in 2011, New Amsterdam Vodka is a brand of E & J Gallo in Modesto, California. Their vodka is grain based and bottled at 40% ABV.
Finlandia first hit the market in 1970, the first Scandinavian vodka in the US. It is distilled from six-row barley and uses glacial spring water to bring it to proof. The vodka is not filtered.

Distilled at the Mariinsk Distillery in Siberia, this vodka is distilled from grain and water from a 300-meter Siberian deep well. The vodka rests from 30-90 days before bottling. Please note that additives of honey, oat extract, and milk thistle are including in the bottling.

Svedka--a mashed up word taking "svenska" meaning "Swedish" and vodka--was first introduced in 1998. It is column-distilled from Swedish winter wheat. Svedka is now owned by Constellation Brands based in the US.
This vodka is made from Polish Dankowski rye using continuous column distillation. Named after the Polish King Jan III Sobieski who reigned from 1674 until his death in 1696. Bottled at 40% ABV.
Luksusowa, Polish for "luxury", is a vodka distilled from potatoes. The vodka is copper column-distilled and rectified before adding water to bring to 40% ABV. The vodka is filtered for clarity.

This ultra premium vodka first hit the market in 2003. Stoli Elit is made using "freeze filtration" inspired by the old Russian tradition of leaving casks outside in plummeting winter conditions. This grain based (wheat and rye) vodka is bottled at 40% ABV.
Kirkland American Vodka is the Costco label vodka. It's "distilled six times" from an undisclosed base or distillery.

Haku Vodka is made from 100% Japanese white rice which is milled and polished. The white rice is fermented with koji rice to create a mash that is then distilled in a pot still. For the second distillation, it goes through two different processes in a pot and column still. The vodka is blended then filtered through bamboo charcoal and is proofed to 40% ABV. The curved lines on the bottle are meant to represent the streams glistening through nature in Japan as they run through the four seasons. Haku Vodka was exclusive released to the US in October 2018.
One of the Russian Standard bottlings, this vodka is distilled from 100% Russian winter wheat. It is distilled in St. Petersburg and filtered through a "silver filtration system". Bottled at 40% ABV.

This vodka is produced from 100% organically-grown sugarcane and mineral rich ocean water sourced 3,000 feet deep, off the Kona Coast in Hawaii. Distilled using a continuous column process on the island of Maui.

Koskenkorva Vodka has been around since 1953, but it only launched in the US in 2017. It is a vodka made via continuous distillation from Finnish barley sourced within 120 miles from the distillery. Local spring water is used in its production. Named after the village where it is made.

Deep Eddy Vodka is a corn-based vodka. It is column-distilled and charcoal filtered before Texas water is added to bring the vodka to proof. It first hit the market in 2011, a year after the brand's Sweet Tea version. Deep Eddy Distillery is located in Buda, Texas just outside Austin where the brand's headquarters and Deep Eddy Pool is located. This freshwater swimming pool is the oldest pool in Texas and is the inspiration for the vodka's namesake.

This vodka is distilled in France from wheat grain found in the northern France. This brand is more known for the dozens of flavors it sells. Filtered spring water is used to bring the vodka to proof. Bottled in Frankfort, Kentucky.

This vodka from Hangar 1 is distilled from Midwestern grains and wine grapes. The distillery is located in a hangar on the grounds of the now-closed Alameda Naval Air Station. Hangar 1 distills a myriad of flavored vodkas, some only seasonally.

Elyx is made from 100% single-estate winter wheat sourced from the Råbelöf Castle near Åhus where Absolut is made. It is distilled in a single column-still made entirely of copper. First launched in select markets in 2011, was released in the US in 2013. "Lyx" is the Swedish word for "luxury".

Wyborowa Wódka, pronounced "vee-bo-rova" was founded in 1927 and translates to "excellent." Wyborowa, commonly referred to as Wybo, is a Polish vodka, which must be made from cereals or potatoes grown in Poland, contain no additives other than water, and be produced in Poland. Wybo is produced from pure rye grain and water from the Wyborowa well and bottled at 37.5% ABV.

Prairie Organic Vodka is distilled from non-GMO organic corn sourced from farmers in Minnesota. After harvest, the corn is brought to a co-op farm where the corn is milled, mashed, and fermented. This fermented mash is then taken to the Prairie distillery where it is column-distilled.
A product of the Ukraine, Nemiroff Original is a wheat-based vodka that's filtered 11 times. Bottled at 40% ABV.

ZYR is distilled from Russian winter wheat and rye with water sourced from northwest Russia. After distillation, it is filtered through birch tree charcoal granules. ZYR is short for the Russian phrase "zyrkalo mira" meaning "reflection of the world".
This vodka was first introduced in 1996. It is made from 100% American grains and is "seven times distilled", hence the name. Bottled at 40%. Produced and bottled by the Sazerac Company.

This vodka from Nikka uses a base of corn and barley malt distillate which were distilled in a Coffey Still as the name suggests. The corn and barley malt were individually distilled and blended, diluted, and filtered with white birch charcoal. Bottled at 40% ABV.

This vodka is distilled from wheat, rye, and potatoes--not something you see every day. Made in Poland, this vodka is a product of the Patrón Spirits Company. Packaged in a eye-catching blue cobalt bottle. It is 40% ABV.
This vodka's origins date back to 1782. It is a potato-based vodka and has a distinct blue label. It is popular in Poland and the US in addition to its home country of Austria.

Broken Shed Vodka is made using a distillate base of whey, the by-product of dairy processing. It is triple distilled and uses water from both the South and North islands of New Zealand. It is certified gluten-free, Non-GMO, and has no additives, sugars or sweeteners added.

Purity is made from organic barley and winter wheat. What they make at their distillery in Sweden is the heart of the vodka. There they use a 600-liter copper pot-still which is attached to two column stills, each with eight plates. The mash of winter wheat and barley is distilled through twice creating a spirit which doesn't need filtration. This is blended with an organic column-distilled wheat distillate and two types of water: de-ionized water and mineral-rich water. Bottled at 40% ABV, this vodka is certified organic in the US and the EU.
EFFEN is a vodka distilled from French wheat using water sourced from a local reservoir. It is distilled in a stainless-steel continuous column-still and filtered using active charcoal filtration.

This American-made vodka is distilled from corn sourced from Kansas, Missouri, and Oklahoma. Water from Lake Fort Smith in Arkansas is added to bring the vodka to proof. It is charcoal filtered and brought down to 40% ABV.

Blue Ice American Potato Vodka is produced in Idaho using russet potatoes. It takes nearly 10 pounds of potatoes to make one bottle of Blue Ice. The vodka is filtered five times, through a filter press, charcoal, travertine, crystal or garnet and submicron.

Made just like the classic Red No. 21 vodka, but bottled at higher proof. It is distilled via continuous distillation and made from grain. It is charcoal filtered and bottled at 50% ABV. It is known in some markets and travel retail as "Export Strength" or "No. 57 Export Strength".
This is a higher-proof version of Finlandia's standard vodka. It is distilled from six-row barley and uses glacial spring water to bring it to proof of 101 (50.5% ABV).
Rain is a vodka which is distilled from corn. Pure limestone water is used in its production. Bottled at 40% ABV. Its bottle states "vodka with natural flavors".

Imperia is distilled in St. Petersburg and is a part of the Russian Standard vodka line. The vodka is distilled from 100% Russian winter wheat. It is filtered through quartz crystal sourced from the Ural Mountains. The vodka rests for 72 hours prior to bottling.
Introduced in 2011 as the second extension in the Chopin portfolio. It is made from 100% golden rye grown in the Podlasie countryside in eastern Poland. Distilled in a copper column-still.

Castle & Key Restoration Release Vodka is made with one of three mash bills (selection of grains), indicated on each bottle. These mash bills form the base for the brand's upcoming bourbon and rye whiskeys. One is made with 73% white corn, 10% rye, 17% malted barley. Another is made with 73% white corn, 10% wheat, and 17% malted barley. And finally, one is made with 17% yellow corn, 63% rye, and 20% malted barley. The limited edition vodka is bottled at 80 proof and available at the distillery and at select Kentucky and Tennessee retailers.

Crystal Head Aurora is the luxury release of Crystal Head Vodka, a brand owned by noted ghostbuster, Dan Aykroyd. The grain used here is English wheat rather than the peaches and creamed corn variety used in its original version. After distillation, the vodka is filtered seven times with three of the runs through Herkimer quartz "diamonds." The packaging mimics the light phenomenon aurora borealis.

Launched in 2010 in the US, Unfiltered is distilled from 100% Polish Dankowskie Diamond rye. It is distilled using a four column-still process. The rye used comes from a single-estate and is "Baker's grade". Additionally, as the name suggests, it is not filtered. Bottled at 40% ABV.

상품명: BELUGA TRANSATLANTIC RACING SPECIAL EDITION VODKA

설명: Made in the United Kingdom from British wheat, this vodka is the "naked", or no flavor added offering from Three Olives. It undergoes a quadruple distillation and filtration process before bottling. It is bottled at 40% ABV.

상품명: BELVEDERE SINGLE ESTATE RYE: LAKE BARTĘŻEK
설명: First announced in fall 2017, this single-estate vodka gets all of its rye from a farm on the lakeside village of Lake Bartężek in northeastern Poland. Diamond Dankowskie rye is grown and harvested here for Belvedere. This vodka is intended to explore the idea of terroir and joins their other single-estate rye, Smogóry Forest, in this endeavor. Expected release for both vodkas to occur in early 2018.

Eristoff Vodka was first produced in the 19th century with the original recipe dating back to 1806. Named after the Eristoff family who ruled the area dubbed "Land of the Wolf", a wolf adorns the bottle. This vodka is 100% grain-based and after distillation it is brought to proof using demineralized water. It is charcoal-filtered and bottled at 40% ABV.
Boyd & Blair is made from 100% Pennsylvanian potatoes. The vodka is triple-batch distilled in a 1200-liter copper hybrid still. The vodka is filled, waxed, and corked by hand.

This vodka is distilled from Midwestern non-GMO corn and is gluten free. It is also certified Kosher by the Houston Kashruth Association. It is filtered through Swedish activated charcoal and bottled at 40% ABV.

FRÏS Vodka is pronounced “frees” and its name is meant to evoke the brand's unique and patented Freeze Filtered Process. The details of this procedure are not readily defined but the brand does boast a pure wheat base. Distilled in Denmark and blended with purified water before bottling at 80 proof.

Located in West Dorset, England; Black Cow is the creation of dairy farmer Jason Barber. The milk from his grass-grazing dairy cows is used in its production. More specifically, it is the whey from the cow's milk to which yeast is added to ferment into a "beer" (the curds are used to create cheddar cheese). This vodka is triple filtered and bottled at 40% ABV.

This Vermont-based vodka is distilled from raw honey. The honey is cold-fermented for three weeks before distillation is done in custom-made stills. The vodka bottle is sealed with beeswax and comes in at 80 proof. Sold in 375ml and 750ml sized bottles.

상품명: BELVEDERE SINGLE ESTATE RYE: SMOGÓRY FOREST
설명: First announced in fall 2017 during London Cocktail Week, this single-estate vodka gets all of its rye from a farm in the village of Smogóry Forest in western Poland. Diamond Dankowskie rye is grown and harvested here for Belvedere. This vodka is intended to explore the idea of terroir and joins their other single-estate rye, Lake Bartężek, in this endeavor. Expected release for both vodkas to occur in early 2018.

Iceberg Vodka is an entirely Canadian production. Icebergs are harvested annually as they break off from Greenland and head south. The water is melted and used as the water which brings the vodka down to proof. The vodka itself is made from Ontario sweet corn and distilled in St. John, Newfoundland.

High West is perhaps better known for their rye whiskey releases, but they do produce a vodka. They consider this an "oat-flavored" vodka. They distill 85% oats along with 15% malted barley. They then blend that with a base vodka made from wheat and corn. The vodka is not chill-filtered or carbon treated. 7000' is the exact elevation of their bar at the distillery in Park City, Utah.

Made in Missouri using locally sourced corn, 360 Vodka is "eco-friendly" and gluten free. Their bottle is made from recycled glass, recycled paper, and printed using eco-friendly ink. Bottled at 40% ABV.

This farm-to-bottle vodka uses 100% potatoes which are grown on their family farm just outside Aspen, Colorado. The potatoes, after mashing and fermentation, are distilled in their custom Carl stills. Naturally gluten-free. Bottled at 40% ABV.

Double Cross is distilled from estate-grown winter wheat using spring water from the Tatra Mountains. It is filtered using a combination of old and new technologies including a diamond-dust filter. The striking bottle showcases Slovakian poetry quotes inscribed on the glass. Bottled at 40%.

Pravda is distilled from Polish rye. It is five-column distilled and then placed in a copper pot-still for its final distillation. Water from the springs of the Carpathian Mountains are used in its production and gently filtered. The vodka itself is filtered through charcoal made from French birchwood. Bottled at 40% ABV.
Seagram's Extra Smooth vodka used American grains in its production. Bottled at 40% ABV.

U'luvka is a Polish vodka distilled from wheat, rye, barley, and oats grown in the Wielkopolska region of Poland. The bottle design is "inspired by ancient alchemist distillation vessels". Some bottles are sold with two drinking vessels which have no base, a gentle suggestion to never put your glass down.

This Midwestern spirit is crafted from 100% white wine grapes in Bloomington Indiana. Distilled to 190.5 proof, the goal is to maintain some of the grapes’ inherent flavor. Charcoal-filtration is employed to remove any unwanted flavors.
This vodka is made from a mix of winter wheat and rye. The water used in its production is sourced from wells over 300-feet deep. Charcoal filtered and bottled at 40% ABV.
Released in 2016, this vodka from Stoli is made from corn (88%) and buckwheat (12%). Distilled in Russia and bottled and brought to proof in Riga, Latvia.

Great Lakes Distillery, founded by Guy Rehorst, is located in Milwaukee, Wisconsin. Spirits are hand made in small batches using traditional methods and local ingredients. Rehorst Vodka has a mash of Wisconsin grown red wheat and red wheat malt. Only the middle cut is used and bottled at 40% ABV.

Distilled in Atchison, Kansas, TILL American Vodka aims to celebrate the American heartland. Distilled from wheat, its name refers to the farm tool used to work soil. The brand is owned by MGP Ingredients, which is widely known for contract whiskey distilling out of its Lawrenceburg, Indiana distillery.

Distilled in a small town in California’s Humboldt County, this vodka is distilled from sugarcane and is USDA certified organic. It is also non-GMO and gluten free. The locale boasts access to a pure water source among an old growth redwood forest which is used to bring the proof down to 80 before bottling.

Launched in May 2018 by spirits giant Diageo, this vodka is made in the US. Corn from Indiana and Iowa make up its base and it is naturally gluten-free. American Anthem will donate $1 from each bottle made, split between 'Operation Gratitude' and 'The Mission Continues' -- two charitable organizations that are dedicated to strengthening and supporting military personnel and their families.
Made by Watershed Distillery in Columbus, Ohio, this vodka was first introduced in 2010. It is made from a base of locally-sourced corn and apples. Bottled at 40% ABV.
Potocki is made from 100% locally-sourced rye. Distilled via column distillation, it is blended with distilled water to bring it to proof. No additives and no charcoal filtration.

Based in California’s Sonoma County, Hanson makes its vodka using organic grapes from the area. This Sonoma wine is then distilled on a combination pot still and fifty-plate column still to create the spirit. The vodka is not only organic, but it is also non-GMO and gluten free.

This 90 proof vodka is made just like its classic brother, but bottled at a slightly higher proof. Smirnoff is distilled via continuous distillation and made from grain. It is charcoal filtered and bottled at 45% ABV.

This vodka, first launched in 2006, is distilled in Poland using spelt grain and natural spring water. This vodka was created to help the endangered snow leopard. 15% of all profits go to the Snow Leopard Trust, a non-profit organization established in 1981.
This Polish vodka is made from 100% rye. After column-distillation it is twice charcoal-filtered. Bottled at 40% ABV.

상품명: BLOOD X SWEAT X TEARS VODKA
설명: Blood x Sweat x Tears Vodka is made by a team of self-labeled "misfits"in Eugene, Oregon. It's made using locally-sourced Pacific Northwest wheat and is freeze filtered. The final product is hand bottled at 40% ABV.

Social House Vodka is produced by Social Beverage Company at the Three Stacks Vodka Distillery in Kinston, NC. It is made with 100% North Carolina corn. After being distilled five times, it is cut with water from the Black Creek Aquifer to bring the it down to 40% ABV.
Starr Blue vodka is an American grain vodka that's been distilled five times. It is produced in Minnesota by United States Distilled Products and is bottled at 40% ABV.
Crown Russe Vodka is produced by Sazerac Company in Frankfort, KY. This vodka came under the Sazerac brand umbrella in 1989 when Sazerac purchased it along with several other brands from Seagram.

Purity Distillery is located on the Ellinge Castle estate in Sweden. The brand makes a variety of certified organic vodkas (as well as gin) with varying numbers of distillations. Each of the vodkas is made with both malted barley and Swedish winter wheat. The mash is run through the copper still system consisting of a 600-liter pot still connected to two column stills, each with 8 plates. For this Connoisseur 51 Reserve, it is run through three times with each plate considered a distillation. This heart is collected and blended with column-distilled organic wheat spirit. It's proofed to 40% ABV with mineral-rich Swedish water and deionized water.

Chase Original Potato Vodka is made in Herefordshire by field-to-bottle Chase Distillery. Three types of potatoes are grown here: King Edward, Lady Claire, and Lady Rosetta. They are processed and distilled in a copper pot still named "Fat Betty." It takes about 250 potatoes to create each bottle.

Made at the Tom's Town Distilling Co. in Kansas City, the two grains used for the brand's vodka are wheat (90%) and Missouri rye (10%). Note: This vodka was formerly known as Eli's StrongArm Vodka. Brand and bottle update in 2018.

This vodka is made in Ontario from Niagara-grown grapes. These grapes were shaken from their vines during the thinning process. Instead of them being discarded, wine and then vodka was made instead. This wine base was distilled three times in their hybrid copper still to a 95% ABV, hence the name.

Crater Lake products were first made in Bend, Oregon. Then in 2010 they moved their distillery to Tumalo, Oregon. Their standard vodka is distilled from grain. It is filtered ten times through charcoal and crushed lava rock. This is to imitate the natural filtration that happens to the water of Crater Lake. A portion of each batch is rested briefly in new American oak barrels.

상품명: ST. GEORGE SPIRITS ALL PURPOSE VODKA
설명: This vodka from St. George Spirits in Alameda, California is made from a base of pears and grain. Bartlett pears, the same the distillery uses in their pear brandy, are distilled to 95.1% ABV. They then blend this with a non-GMO grain base spirit. Bottled at 40% ABV after filtering for impurities.

DASH Vodka's distillery, located in Brookshire, Texas, is owned and operated by Master distiller Ali Ansari, founder of Limited Spirits LLC and DASH Vodka. It houses a custom-designed, handcrafted copper pot still from Scotland and a fully automated bottling line. Dash's vodkas are made using organic wheat, sun-roasted Thomson raisins, and traditional fermentation and distillation processes. Dash's Traditional Vodka is distilled seven times and finished with purified mineral water that has been filtered through crushed coconut shells, plate filtered, and micro-oxygenated. Finally, it is bottled at 40% ABV.

Launched November 2019, King St. Vodka is a brand backed by actress/entrepreneur Kate Hudson. It is named for King Street in NYC which was her former home. Distilled in California, King St. is gluten free and made with non-GMO corn. Alkaline water is used in its production. Bottled at 43% ABV.

상품명: MISSISSIPPI RIVER DISTILLING COMPANY RIVER PILOT VODKA

설명: Like the standard Belvedere Vodka bottling, Belvedere Intense 100 Proof Vodka is distilled from 100% Polish Dankowskie rye. In this case, the vodka is only brought down to 100 proof rather than 80 proof. Sold in global travel retail outlets.

Relaunched in late 2017, Stoli Gold has changed their recipe as well as updated their bottle. The vodka is based on 100% single-estate Gubernator Dona winter wheat. The water used in this vodka has been filtered through shungite, a meteoric rock found in the Tambov region in Russia. The vodka is filtered like their standard Stoli, through Russian birch charcoal and quartz sand, but it also is filtered through coils of gold thread. Available first in travel retail at Heathrow and Dubai airports with a wider release expected thereafter.

This is a higher proof version of the classic Absolut Vodka. The black bottle with silver lettering replaced Absolut Red in the late aughts to better differentiate between the classic bottle and the higher proof version. Absolut is produced in the town of Åhus in Sweden from locally-grown winter wheat. Absolut 100 is bottled at 50% ABV.

Pearl Vodka is a Canadian project focused on making classic, smooth vodkas. Wheat from Alberta is distilled five times and cut with water from the Canadian Rockies. The resulting spirit is repeatedly filtered for an easy, highly mixable style.

This vodka is distilled from fair-trade organic quinoa sourced from the Andean Mountains. The quinoa is shipped to Cognac, France where it is distilled by Master Distiller Philip Lacile. In addition to vodka, FAIR makes gin, rum, and several liqueurs. Under the brand's fair trade policies, farmers in developing regions around the world receive a fair profit for the crops they grow.

This is Stoli's 100 Proof bottling, also called Blue Label. This grain based (wheat and rye) vodka is distilled in Russia and bottled and brought to proof in Latvia. It is filtered through Russian birch charcoal and quartz sand.

Santa Fe Spirits was founded in 2010 by Colin Keegan. The New Mexican distillery produces various whiskeys and other spirits including this vodka. Expedition American West Vodka is made using 100% maize (corn) and Sangre de Cristo Mountain water. It is bottled at 80 proof.

The 2021 refresh of this vodka was created in concert with a collective of experts including chemists, professional bartenders, and a water sommelier to achieve the final product. The effect is meant to evoke the naturally occurring salinity and minerality of the waters surrounding its home town of San Francisco, made with vodka + soda drinkers in mind.

This vodka is made using the brand's bourbon mash bill as its base: 73% yellow corn, 17% malted barley, and 10% rye. It's bottled at 80 proof. Note: This vodka is the same as the brand's Restoration Vodka, but with an updated package and name.

상품명: DEEP RUN PIONEER SPIRIT SMALL BATCH VIRGINIA VODKA

설명: Wisconsin-based La Crosse Distilling Co. is the maker of Fieldnotes Vodkas and Gins. They are a grain-to-glass distiller using organic ingredients from local and regional family farmers whenever possible. For their Organic Potato Vodka, regional organic potatoes are used. It is bottled at 40% ABV and is gluten free.
UV Vodka is produced by Phillips Distilling in Minneapolis, Minnesota. It is made using yellow corn, is distilled four times, and is bottled at 40% ABV.

Made on New Zealand’s North Island, VDKA 6100 is distilled from regionally sourced whey, which is fermented with a strain of yeast imported from Ireland. It is then blended with local spring water and bottled at 40% ABV. Its name refers to the distance in miles between New Zealand and the United States, where the brand got its start.

Dingle Vodka is produced in the small town Irish for which it is named. It is made by taking grain alcohol and redistilling it in a copper pot still in 500-liter batches. As of late 2018, this vodka is available in the US.

This farm-to-bottle vodka is distilled from a trio of vodkas grown on their estate: Maris Piper, King Edward, and Cultra. All steps of production are done onsite in Angus, Scotland from harvesting to labeling the bottles. Bottled at 43% ABV.
Van Gogh Vodka is made by third generation master distiller Tim Vos. It is composed of a blend of wheat from Holland, Germany, and France. The brand has grown quite a bit since its start in 2001.

This product was originally created by the Sidney Frank Importing Company, the creator of Grey Goose Vodka. It has recently (2017) been acquired by the Beach Whiskey Company. This isn’t entirely vodka, it also contains agave nectar, hence the name “Vodka Specialty.” This is USDA certified organic and bottled at 40% ABV.
Van Hoo is made entirely from grains and distilled 5 times using column and alembic stills. The distillate is then subjected to a “special charcoal filtering” before being bottled at 40% ABV.

Produced and bottled by Blackwater Spirits located on Kent Island, Md. in the Chesapeake Bay. They source two neutral spirits, one made from organic wheat and one from organic sugarcane. They blend the two spirits (80% wheat, 20% sugarcane) then filter and dilute to make their spirit 80 proof. Named for the sloop named Betty, a merchant vessel filled with Madeira wine captured by Blackbeard in early 18th century off of Cape Charles.

Denver-based Leopold Bros. handle each step of making their vodka from mashing and fermenting to bottling and labeling. Their vodka, uniquely, is made from potatoes, malted barley, and summer wheat. It is lightly-filtered and bottled at 40% ABV.

Like many things in the food and beverage world, Crater Lake’s Reserve Vodka was created by accident. Upon making batch 333 of their standard vodka (which is filtered 10 times through charcoal and crushed lava rock) it was mistakenly left to filter over 100 times. The resulting vodka surprised and impressed the Crater Lake team. Today they create limited releases of their Reserve Vodka to celebrate the happy accident. Made from grain.

Spring 44 seeks to harness the purity of their water source in their Colorado born spirits. The spring is located in Buckhorn Canyon at 2,000 feet elevation and surrounded by 160,000 acres of National forest. Made from a blend of wheat, corn and rye.

One Eight Distilling is based in Washington D.C. They source from three different locations for the grain to make their vodka. Rye sourced from Virginia, malted rye from North Carolina, and corn from Maryland. They use “Russian filtering technology” to achieve a smoother consistency. In spring 2018, their core line of products received a makeover and updated brand name to District Made.

Distilled from winter wheat and rye. The water sourced for its production comes from wells over 300 feet deep. Charcoal filtered. Each bottle of this vodka from Jewel of Russia is individually hand-painted and signed by the artist. The design changes regularly making this a collectible item. Limited availability.

This is a gluten-free vodka from Eastern Idaho, made from locally sourced Russet potatoes. While Simple Vodka is friend to local farmers and the environment, their real mission is to fight hunger in America. Through partnerships with local and national hunger relief programs Simple Vodka is able to donate 20 meals for every bottle purchased. Since launching in May 2017, they have donated 29,000 meals and aim to donate 30 million meals annually by 2020.
This Diageo owned product is made from grain neutral spirit. Bottled at 40% ABV in a variety of bottle sizes, often in plastic.

Hailing from creole country in Louisiana, the Donner-Peltier opened with the mission to create the world’s most premium vodka. Oryza Vodka is distilled 17 times and the use of purified water and hi-tech filtration aim to make a hyper smooth and luxurious product. A key separator from the pack is the southern accent of using local, long-grain rice. Update: Donner-Peltier Distillers, the Thibodaux-based distillery, announced that it will cease operations after Monday, August 27, 2018

This vodka is made from winter wheat sourced from farmers near the Western Rockies of Canada where it is distilled. It is continuously-distilled in three separate copper-plated column-stills. Though it is distilled in Canada, the vodka is brought down to proof in Northern California using water from Mendocino County. It is not carbon-filtered to ensure a flavorful vodka.

This vodka is made from a variety of "virgin new potatoes" from Cape Bjäre, Sweden--potatoes picked early in the season when the skin has just started to form. These varieties include solist, gammel svensk röd, princess, sankta thora, hamlet, marine and celine. Each varietal is distilled once through a copper-lined continuous still. The separate distillates are then blended together without charcoal-filtering.

Dirty Devil Vodka was created and launched in Quebec, Canada in 2019. It is made from non-GMO corn and hyper-oxygenated water, a process which introduces 5 times the amount of oxygen into the water. The base spirit is blended with this water and it is allowed to rest for six weeks before bottling at 84 proof. Available in the US as of April 2021.
